#open-question(title: [Can PEM-Protected Interoceptive Training Improve Symptom Burden in ME/CFS?])[
No interoceptive training/rehabilitation trial has been conducted in ME/CFS — a complete evidence gap. A PEM-protected protocol would operationalise safety constraints: no breath-hold > 50% vital capacity, training only in recumbent/semi-recumbent position, session maximum 20 minutes, any increase in interoceptive distress > 2/10 triggers abort, training frequency 5x/week never 2 consecutive days, training only during non-PEM periods. The core intervention: heartbeat discrimination biofeedback (cardiac interoception) plus emotional granularity training (vocabulary to differentiate low-arousal negative states). Primary outcomes: HBDT accuracy (objective), MAIA-2 (sensibility), FACIT-F (fatigue), PEM frequency at 12 weeks. Design: randomized, waitlist-controlled, n=60 mild-to-moderate ME/CFS. Exclude severe/very-severe patients who cannot safely engage in structured cognitive activities. The mechanistic rationale is that interoceptive training should reduce allostatic load by improving signal quality (better afferent signal → fewer unresolvable prediction errors → lower free energy) — but if the training itself increases allostatic load, it defeats the purpose. The PEM-protected protocol operationalises this constraint. (Origin: brainstorm) @Garfinkel2015interoceptionAccuracy @GreenhouseTucknott2022predictiveCodingFatigue
